# About the iREAL Dashboard

Welcome to the iREAL (Inclusive Requirements Elicitation for AI in Libraries) Dashboard. This interactive tool presents data from 49 Aboriginal schools in New South Wales, Australia, spanning the 19th to early 20th century. The information has been extracted from historical records using AI and machine learning techniques, aiming to support the development of an approach for libraries to respectfully manage Indigenous Knowledges in an AI deployment/development context.

## Project Overview and Architecture

The iREAL project is an initiative to develop an inclusive requirements elicitation system for AI in libraries, with a focus on Indigenous Australian communities. Our system architecture consists of four main components:

1. **Data collection**: Historical records about NSW Aboriginal schools from [NRS-3829 (part) List of Aboriginal school files, 1876–1979](https://mhnsw.au/articles/3829/)
2. **Data pre-processing**: Conversion of original documents into JSON and Markdown formats for analysis and rendering.
3. **Data extraction**: Use of AI/ML models to extract metadata, including entities, keywords, topics, and geographical information.
4. **Dashboard**: This SvelteKit-built frontend interface for data exploration and visualisation.

## Data Extraction Techniques

We employ several AI/ML techniques to extract meaningful information:

- **Entity extraction**: Using [SpanMarker](https://huggingface.co/tomaarsen/span-marker-mbert-base-multinerd) to identify persons, organisations, locations, diseases, and years.
- **Geocoding**: Matching extracted locations against a [CSV file](https://data.gov.au/dataset/ds-dga-11cbf24a-a31a-488c-bc65-2811da2a8582/details?q=ABoriginal%20welfare%20board) of NSW place coordinates.
- **Keyword extraction**: Using [Mistral 7B](https://docs.mistral.ai/getting-started/models/) LLM to extract top 5 thematic keywords per text chunk.
- **Topic extraction**: Using the LLM with a custom prompt to identify overarching topics.

## Dashboard Features

- **School Profiles**: Detailed information about each Aboriginal school, including historical context and extracted metadata.
- **Topic and Keyword Exploration**: Discover common themes and important terms.
- **Organisations Exploration**: Examine referenced organisations and their frequency of mention.
- **Interactive Map**: Explore the geographical distribution of schools.

## Ethical Considerations

The iREAL project is committed to the respectful and ethical management of Indigenous Knowledges. While AI and machine learning techniques have been used to process this historical data, we acknowledge the importance of human interpretation and Indigenous perspectives in understanding this information.

## Feedback and Further Information

We welcome feedback on this dashboard and the wider iREAL project. For more information about the technical implementation, please refer to our [GitHub repository](https://github.com/kingsdigitallab/ireal).

This project is a collaboration between University of Glasgow, the Jumbunna Institute for Indigenous Education and Research (University of Technology Sydney) and King's Digital Lab (King's College London), supported by the Arts and Humanities Research Council under the Bridging Responsible AI Divides Scheme [BRAID, grant number AH/Z505638/1]. It has been developed with deep respect for the Indigenous communities of New South Wales.
